:::summary
Forests are among God's most magnificent creations — complex, multi-layered communities of trees, plants, animals, fungi, and microorganisms that cover about 31 percent of Earth's land surface and perform essential ecological services for the entire planet. They regulate climate, purify water, cycle nutrients, shelter biodiversity, and have sustained human civilizations for millennia through timber, food, medicine, and inspiration. From the cedars of Lebanon celebrated in Scripture to the ancient forests of the American frontier, forests have been woven into the story of faith, culture, and civilization.
:::

